Section 1:
1 L.D. 1511
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
4 Reproduced and distributed under the direction of the Clerk of the House.
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 995, L.D. 1511, “An Act to Expand
10 Direct Health Care Service Arrangements”
11 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
12 following:
13 'Sec. 1. 22 MRSA c. 403-A, headnote is amended to read:
14 CHAPTER 403-A
15 DIRECT PRIMARY HEALTH CARE SERVICE AGREEMENTS
16 Sec. 2. 22 MRSA §1771, as enacted by PL 2017, c. 112, §1, is amended to read:
17 §1771. Direct primary health care service agreements
18 1. Definitions. As used in this section, unless the context otherwise indicates, the
19 following terms have the following meanings.
20 A. "Direct primary health care service agreement" means a contractual agreement
21 between a direct primary health care provider and an individual patient, or the patient's
22 legal representative, in which:
23 (1) The direct primary health care provider agrees to provide primary health care
24 services to the individual patient for an agreed-to fee over an agreed-to period of
25 time; and
26 (2) The direct primary health care provider agrees not to bill 3rd parties on a fee-
27 for-service or capitated basis for services already covered in the direct primary
28 health care service agreement.
29 B. "Direct primary health care provider" means an individual who is a licensed
30 allopathic physician or osteopathic physician or other advanced health care practitioner
31 who is authorized to engage in independent medical practice in this State, who is
Page 1 - 132LR1901(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 995, L.D. 1511
312 qualified to provide primary care services and who chooses to practice direct primary
323 health care by entering into a direct primary health care service agreement with
334 patients. The term includes, but is not limited to, an individual primary health care
345 provider or a group of primary health care providers.
5 C. "Primary care" means outpatient, nonspecialty health care services or the
6 coordination of health care for the purpose of:
7 (1) Promoting or maintaining mental and physical health and wellness; and
8 (2) The diagnosis, treatment or management of acute or chronic conditions caused
9 by disease, injury or illness.
10 D. "Health care" has the same meaning as in section 1711-C, subsection 1, paragraph
11 C.
12 2. Not insurance. A direct primary health care service agreement is not an insurance
13 policy and is not subject to regulation by the Department of Professional and Financial
14 Regulation, Bureau of Insurance.
15 3. Ability to contract. A direct primary health care service agreement is an agreement
16 between the direct primary health care provider and either an individual or the individual's
17 representative, regardless of whether the periodic fee or other fees are paid by the
18 individual, the individual's representative or a 3rd party.
19 4. Covered services. A direct primary health care service agreement covers only the
20 services specified in the agreement. Any goods or services that are not covered by the
21 direct primary health care service agreement may be billed separately.
22 5. Disclosure. A direct primary health care service agreement must clearly state within
23 the agreement that direct primary health care services are not considered health insurance
24 and do not meet requirements of any federal law mandating individuals to purchase health
25 insurance and that the fees charged in the agreement may not be reimbursed or apply
26 towards a deductible under a health insurance policy with an insurer.
27 6. Other care not prohibited. A primary health care provider is considered a direct
28 primary health care provider only when the provider is engaged in a direct primary health
29 care service agreement with a patient or group of patients. A primary health care provider
30 is not prohibited from providing care to other patients under a separate agreement or
31 contract with an insurer.
32 7. Other agreements not prohibited. This section does not prohibit a direct primary
33 health care provider from entering into:
34 A. An agreement with an insurer offering a policy specifically designed to supplement
35 a direct primary health care service agreement; or
36 B. A pilot program for direct primary care or direct health care with a federal or state
37 agency that provides health coverage.
38 Sec. 3. 24-A MRSA §4303, sub-§22, as amended by PL 2019, c. 178, §1, is further
39 amended to read:
40 22. Denial of referral by out-of-network provider prohibited. Beginning January
41 1, 2018, a carrier may not deny payment for any health care service covered under an
42 enrollee's health plan based solely on the basis that the enrollee's referral was made by a
Page 2 - 132LR1901(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 995, L.D. 1511
413 direct primary health care provider who is not a member of the carrier's provider network.
424 A carrier may not apply a deductible, coinsurance or copayment greater than the applicable
435 deductible, coinsurance or copayment that would apply to the same health care service if
446 the service was referred by a participating primary care provider. A carrier may require a
457 direct primary health care provider making a referral who is not a member of the carrier's
468 provider network to provide information demonstrating that the provider is a direct primary
479 health care provider through a written attestation or copy of a direct primary health care
580 service agreement with an enrollee and may request additional information necessary to
591 implement this subsection. As used in this subsection, "direct primary health care provider"
1502 has the same meaning as in Title 22, section 1771, subsection 1, paragraph B.'
11 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
12 number to read consecutively.
13 SUMMARY
1144 This amendment replaces the bill. Under current law an individual can contract directly
1155 with a direct primary care provider who is a licensed allopathic or osteopathic physician or
1166 other advanced health care practitioner who is authorized to provide primary care services
1177 for the provision of health care to that individual. This amendment removes the
1188 requirement that the physician or advanced health care practitioner be authorized to provide
1199 primary care services.
20 The amendment also corrects a cross-reference.
Page 3 - 132LR1901(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
